entry.sense:
tajoniysN mutawoCamN 
† The using two words resembling each other in writing but not in expression; 


as in the saying, gar-aka Eiz-uka faSaAra quSaAru celika cul-aka faQxoXa faAHiXa fiEolika faEal-aka tuhodaA bihecaA [Thy might, or elevated rank, hath deceived thee, and the end of that has become thine ignominy: fear then thine exorbitant deed, and may-be thou wilt be made to follow a right course by this]. (Ḥar p. 269.)

tabiEotu Alr-ajula biHaq-iI; 
and taAbaEotuhu↓ bihi, 
inf. n. mutaAbaEapN [and probably tbaAEN also]; 
and Ait-abaEotuhu↓ bh; I prosecuted, or sued, the man for my right, or due. (TA.) 
The saying in the Ḳur [ii. 173], faQt-ibaAEN↓ biQlomaEoruwfi means [Then] prosecution for the bloodwit [shall be made with lenity]. (TA.)

A servant; 
as also tabiyEN↓. (TA.) Oawi Alt-aAbiEiyna gayori OuwliI AlUirobapi, in the Ḳur [xxiv. 31], 
accord. to Th, means Or the servants of the husband, such as the old man who is perishing by reason of age, and the aged woman. (TA.)

Also Cleaving to the dust by reason of want; having nothing between him and the earth: (IAạr, T:) [cleaving to the dust by reason of poverty; 
see 1:] poor, as though cleaving to the dust: (Mṣb:) and [simply,] poor: (IAạr, T, TA:) or needy, or in want. (M.) 
[See also mutoribN.]

Also Insipid; tasteless; 
and so taAfihN↓. (KL.) 
You say OaToEimapN tafihapN Kinds of food having no taste of sweetness, or of sourness, or of bitterness; and some include bread and flesh-meat among these. (Ḳ.)

matolafN 
A place of perishing or perdition: (Ḳ:) a [desert such as is termed] mafaAzap; (Ṣ, Ḳ;) because most of those who traverse it perish; 
and so matolafapN↓; (TA;) or the latter signifies a [desert such as is termed] qafor: (M:) the pl. of the former [or of both] is mataAlifu. (TA.)

hom.sense:
2. tam-amahu: 
see its syn. Atm-hu; 
and see also 1, near the end of the paragraph.

entry.sense:
taAYihN part. n. of 1; Deviating from, or losing, or missing, the right way; losing his way:, &c.: 
see 1; 
and see also art. tyh. (TA.)

tiylN 
[Hemp, of which ropes and cloths are manufactured; thus called by the Arabs in the present day; perhaps from the Persian tiylaA “a rope;”] a certain thing resembling flax, that comes forth from the sea; 
[possibly meaning that it is imported into Arabia;] and of which cloths are woven. (TA.)

mutay-amN 
Enslaved, and brought into subjection, by love: (Ṣ:) having the heart enslaved, and brought into subjection, and affected with vehement love so as to be deprived of his reason: (Abu-l-ʼAbbás El-Ahwal, TA:) or deprived of his reason; disordered therein; by women; 
as also matiymN↓: and led astray. (T.)
